(225, 'E&E6.0', 'Not in Employment Education or Training\nAverage cost per 18-24 year old not in education, employment or training', '4263.00', 2010, 'Youth Unemployment: the crisis we cannot afford (ACEVO Commission on Youth Unemployment, 2012)', 'http://www.cesi.org.uk/sites/default/files/event_downloads/ACEVO_report.pdf', 'High', 'Analysis of data from the Acevo report (costs not updated), calculation as follows: total cost to exchequer nationally per year £4,744,204,046; 723,380 claimants nationally; = £6,558 per person on benefits.  65% of 18-24 year old NEETs claim benefits, therefore cost per NEET is 65% of cost per person on benefits = £4,263', 3, 51, 10, 4, 70, NULL),
(226, 'E&E6.1', 'Not in Employment Education or Training\nAverage cost per 16-17 year old not in education, employment or training', '533.00', 2010, 'Youth Unemployment: the crisis we cannot afford (ACEVO Commission on Youth Unemployment, 2012)', 'http://www.cesi.org.uk/sites/default/files/event_downloads/ACEVO_report.pdf', 'High', 'Analysis of data from the Acevo report (costs not updated), calculation as follows: total cost to exchequer nationally per year £77,099,839 (pg88); 27,500 claimants nationally; = £2,804 per person on benefits.  19% of 16-17 year old NEET population claim benefits, therefore average cost per NEET is 19% of cost per person on benefits = £533.  Note that this cost is based on benefits payments, and therefore care should be taken to avoid double-counting when preparing Troubled Families business plans.', 3, 51, 10, 4, 70, NULL),
(227, 'E&E6.2', 'Not in Employment Education or Training\nLifetime costs - Public finance cost which includes: welfare payment cost £ (- pensions); and lost-contribution £ (NI+ d-tax lost).', '64483.00', 2010, 'Coles et al 2010: Estimating the life-time cost of NEET:\n16-18 year olds not in Education, Employment or Training p37 tab 3.7', '', 'High', 'Presents a calculation of the public finance cost of each of the case studies being NEET. Aggregated the life-time welfare payments of each case with the lost contributions (an estimate of lost tax and National Insurance) because of their unemployment.', 3, 51, 10, 4, 4, NULL),
(228, 'FI1.0', 'Average consequence cost per fire', '3079.00', 2008, 'The economic cost of fire: estimates for 2008 - Fire Research Report 3/2011 (Department for Communities and Local Government, 2011), p.29-30', 'http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121108165934/http:/www.communities.gov.uk/documents/corporate/pdf/1838338.pdf', 'Medium', 'This cost is derived from the constituent cost lines detailed below - it includes the cost per fire of fatalities, injuries and non-detected arson, and costs to the Criminal Justice System, police, and prison service.  Although the latter (agency) costs are fiscal, note that elements of the other costs may not be.  The source also quotes costs per fire for property damage of (2012/13 prices) £2,902, and for lost business of £87; as these are economic rather than fiscal costs, they have not been included in the overall cost quoted here (if included, as per the source, the average consequence cost per fire becomes £6,381).  Quoted costs are averages for England; the source also gives averages for the nine English regions.', 4, 1, 10, 10, 37, NULL),
(229, 'FI2.0', 'Average response cost per fire', '3186.00', 2008, 'The economic cost of fire: estimates for 2008 - Fire Research Report 3/2011 (Department for Communities and Local Government, 2011), p.29-30', 'http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20121108165934/http:/www.communities.gov.uk/documents/corporate/pdf/1838338.pdf', 'Medium', 'This is the response cost per fire incurred by the fire service - it is a fiscal cost, although not one that is easily cashable (avoiding a certain number of responses does not necessarily mean a fire worker or station can be decommissioned).  The cost is an average for England; the source also gives averages for the nine English regions. ', 4, 1, 6, NULL, 37, NULL);
