(247, 'E&S1.0.4', 'Persistent truancy (missing at least five weeks of school per year) - Social Services, per individual per effective year (see comments)', '327.83', 2005, 'Misspent Youth (2007)', 'http://www.thinknpc.org/publications/misspent-youth/', 'Medium', 'Note age of data.  GM CBA model social costs covered elsewhere so figure excluded from truancy cost line.   Data here takes the cost of residential and foster care from the BMJ study. As for health and crime costs, we take the group with conduct problems as a proxy for truants. This totalled an extra £1,967 between the ages of 10 and 16 in 2005 prices.', 2, 50, 8, NULL, 50, 243),
(248, 'E&S2.0', 'Permanent exclusion from school - total fiscal cost of permanent exclusion from school, per individual per effective year', '9219.00', 2005, 'Misspent Youth (2007)', 'http://www.thinknpc.org/publications/misspent-youth/', 'Medium', 'Note age of data.   Data expressed in 2005 figures in 2007 report. Caveat wide range of values depending on case, e.g. no average child excluded.  The source also details the cost of permanent exclusion related to lost earnings, at £529 per effective year (non-updated price, drawn from the lifetime figure quoted in Misspent Youth, based on a 40-year working life); as an economic cost to the individual, rather than a fiscal cost to the public purse, this is not included in the total quoted here.  Note comments on constituent costs below, which explain how the cost per effective year has been calculated.', 2, 23, 10, NULL, 50, NULL),
(249, 'E&S2.0.1', 'Permanent exclusion from school - provision of alternative education (e.g. in a pupil referral unit), per individual per effective year (see comments)', '7181.00', 2005, 'Misspent Youth (2007)', 'http://www.thinknpc.org/publications/misspent-youth/', 'Medium', 'Note age of data.   Assumes that the cost to the education welfare system is only felt over two years when the child is 11 and 12. Per annum figure cited in NPC report.', 2, 23, 8, NULL, 50, 248),
